  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Pour se pratiquer</title>
    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Soit <m>f(x,y) = e^x\cos y</m>. Les tables suivantes donnent des valeurs de <m>f(x,y)</m>.
      </p>

      <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
      <col halign="center"/> <col />  <col halign="center"/> <col /> <col halign="center"/> <col />
      <row>
      <cell>  </cell><cell> <m>x=0</m> </cell><cell> <m>x=0.01</m> </cell><cell> <m>x=0.1</m> </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell> <m>y=-0.1</m> </cell><cell> 0.99500 </cell><cell> 1.00500 </cell><cell> 1.09965 </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell> <m>y=-0.01</m> </cell><cell> 0.99995 </cell><cell> 1.01000 </cell><cell> 1.10512 </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell> <m>y=0</m> </cell><cell> 1.0 </cell><cell> 1.01005 </cell><cell> 1.10517 </cell>
      </row>
      </tabular></sidebyside>

      <p>
      <ol>
      <li>
      Trouvez deux valeurs approximatives différentes pour <m>\pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)</m> en utilisant les données du
      tableau ci-dessus.
      </li><li>
      Trouvez deux valeurs approximatives différentes pour <m>\pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)</m> en utilisant les données du
      tableau ci-dessus.
      </li><li>
      Évaluez <m>\pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)</m> et <m>\pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)</m> exactement.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
      </statement>

      <hint><p>
      Revoir la <xref ref="def_partials"/>.
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      <ol>
      <li>
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(h,0)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=0.1}
      =\frac{1.10517-1}{0.1}
      =1.0517
      </me>
      et
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(h,0)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=0.01}
      =\frac{1.01005-1}{0.01}
      =1.005
      </me>
      </li><li>
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(0,h)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=-0.1}
      =\frac{0.99500-1}{-0.1}
      =0.0500
      </me>
      et
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(0,h)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=-0.01}
      =\frac{0.99995-1}{0.01}
      =.0050
      </me>
      </li><li>
      <m>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0) =1
      </m>
      et
      <m>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0) = 0
      </m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      <ol>
      <li>
      Par définition
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)
      =\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(h,0)-f(0,0)}{h}
      </me>
      One approximation to this is
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(h,0)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=0.1}
      =\frac{1.10517-1}{0.1}
      =1.0517
      </me>
      Another approximation to this is
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(h,0)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=0.01}
      =\frac{1.01005-1}{0.01}
      =1.005
      </me>
      </li><li>
      By definition
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)
      =\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(0,h)-f(0,0)}{h}
      </me>
      One approximation to this is
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(0,h)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=-0.1}
      =\frac{0.99500-1}{-0.1}
      =0.0500
      </me>
      Another approximation to this is
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)
      \approx \left.\frac{f(0,h)-f(0,0)}{h}\right|_{h=-0.01}
      =\frac{0.99995-1}{0.01}
      =.0050
      </me>
      </li><li>
      To take the partial derivative with respect to <m>x</m> at <m>(0,0)</m>,
      we set <m>y=0</m>, differentiate with respect to <m>x</m> and then set <m>x=0</m>. So
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0) = \left.\diff{}{x} e^x\cos 0\right|_{x=0}
      =\left.e^x\right|_{x=0}=1
      </me>
      To take the partial derivative with respect to <m>y</m> at <m>(0,0)</m>,
      we set <m>x=0</m>, differentiate with respect to <m>y</m> and then set <m>y=0</m>. So
      <me>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0) = \left.\diff{}{y} e^0\cos y\right|_{y=0}
      =\left.\sin y\right|_{y=0}
      =0
      </me>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M226 2009D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Soit
      <me>
      f(x,y)=\begin{cases}\frac{x^2y}{x^2+y^2}&amp; \text{si}\ (x,y)\ne (0,0)\\
                      0 &amp; \text{si}\ (x,y)=(0,0)
             \end{cases}
      </me>
      Calculez, directement d'après les définitions,
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      <m>\pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\diff{}{t} f(t,t)\Big|_{t=0}</m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      Pour (a) et (b), se rappeler que <m>\pdiff{f}{x}(x,y)=\lim\limits_{h\to0}\frac{f(x+h,y)-f(x,y)}{h}</m> et
      <m>\pdiff{f}{y}(x,y)=\lim\limits_{h\to0}\frac{f(x,y+h)-f(x,y)}{h}</m>. Pour (c), vous trouvez la dérivée d'une fonction à une variable, disons <m>g(t)</m>, où <me>
      g(t)=f(t,t)=\begin{cases}
                        \frac{t^2t}{t^2+t^2} &amp; \text{si } t\ne 0 \\
                        0                    &amp; \text{si } t= 0
                       \end{cases}
      </me>
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>0</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>0</m></p><p>
      (c) <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a) Par définition
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{f}{x}(0,0)
      &amp;=\lim_{\De x\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(\De x,0)-f(0,0)}{\De x}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\lim_{\De x\rightarrow 0}\frac{\frac{(\De x^2)(0)}{\De x^2+0^2}-0}{\De x}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(b) Par définition
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{f}{y}(0,0)
      &amp;=\lim_{\De y\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(0,\De y)-f(0,0)}{\De y}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\lim_{\De y\rightarrow 0}\frac{\frac{(0^2)(\De y)}{0^2+\De y^2}-0}{\De y}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(c) Par définition
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \diff{}{t} f(t,t)\Big|_{t=0}
      &amp;=\lim_{t\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(t,t)-f(0,0)}{t}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{\frac{(t^2)(t)}{t^2+t^2}-0}{t}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\lim_{t\rightarrow 0}\frac{t/2}{t}
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=\frac{1}{2}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>

