  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Pour mieux comprendre</title>

    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
        Vous traversez un paysage vallonné. Considérez que l'axe des <m>z</m> pointe vers le ciel, que l'axe des <m>x</m> positifs pointe vers le sud, et que l'axe des <m>y</m> positifs pointe vers l'est. Alors le paysage autour de vous est décrit par l'équation <m>z=f(x,y)</m>, avec vous au point <m>(0,0,f(0,0))</m>. La fonction <m>f(x,y)</m> est différentiable.
      </p>

      <p>Supposons que <m>f_y(0,0) \lt 0</m>. Est-t-il possible que vous soyez sur un sommet? Expliquez.
      </p>

      </statement>
      <hint><p>
      Qu'arrive-t-il si vous vous déplacez vers <q>l'arrière,</q> dans la direction des <m>y</m> négatifs?
      </p></hint>
      <answer><p>
      Non: vous pouvez aller plus haut en vous déplaçant dans la direction des <m>y</m> négatifs.
      </p></answer>
      <solution>

      <p>If <m>f_y(0,0) \lt 0</m>, then <m>f(0,y)</m> decreases as <m>y</m> increases from <m>0</m>.
      Thus moving in the positive <m>y</m> direction takes you downhill. This means
      you aren't at the lowest point in a valley, since you can still move downhill.
      On the other hand, as <m>f_y(0,0) \lt 0</m>, <m>f(0,y)</m> also decreases as <m>y</m>
      increases towards <m>0</m> from slightly negative values. Thus if you move in the <em>negative</em> <m>y</m>-direction from <m>y=0</m>, your height <m>z</m> will <em>increase</em>.
      So you are not at a locally highest point<mdash/>you're not at a summit.
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>


    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Montrez que la fonction <m>z(x,y)=\frac{x+y}{x-y}</m> vérifie
      <me>
      x\pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)+y\pdiff{z}{y}(x,y) = 0
      </me>
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      Simplement évaluer <m>x\pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)+y\pdiff{z}{y}(x,y)</m>.
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
        <p>
        Par la règle du quotient,
        <md alignment="alignat">
        <mrow>
        \pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)
        &amp;=\frac{(1)(x-y)-(x+y)(1)}{(x-y)^2}
        &amp;&amp;=\frac{-2y}{(x-y)^2}
        </mrow><mrow>
        \pdiff{z}{y}(x,y)
        &amp;=\frac{(1)(x-y)-(x+y)(-1)}{(x-y)^2}
        &amp;&amp;=\frac{2x}{(x-y)^2}
        </mrow>
        </md>
        Ainsi,
        <me>
        x\pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)+y\pdiff{z}{y}(x,y)
        =\frac{-2xy+2yx}{(x-y)^2}
        =0
        </me>
        </p>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      Par la règle du quotient,
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)
      &amp;=\frac{(1)(x-y)-(x+y)(1)}{(x-y)^2}
      &amp;&amp;=\frac{-2y}{(x-y)^2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{z}{y}(x,y)
      &amp;=\frac{(1)(x-y)-(x+y)(-1)}{(x-y)^2}
      &amp;&amp;=\frac{2x}{(x-y)^2}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      Ainsi,
      <me>
      x\pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)+y\pdiff{z}{y}(x,y)
      =\frac{-2xy+2yx}{(x-y)^2}
      =0
      </me>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>


    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Soit <m>f</m> une fonction différentiable quelconque d'une variable. Définissez
      <m>z(x,y)=f(x^2+y^2)</m>. Est-ce que l'équation
      <me>
      y\pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)-x\pdiff{z}{y}(x,y) = 0
      </me>
      est nécessairement satisfaite?
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      Simplement évaluer <m>y\pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)</m> et <m>x\pdiff{z}{y}(x,y)</m>.
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      Oui.
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      As <m>z(x,y)=f(x^2+y^2)</m>
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{z}{x}(x,y)&amp;=2xf'(x^2+y^2)
      </mrow><mrow>
      \pdiff{z}{y}(x,y)&amp;=2yf'(x^2+y^2)
      </mrow>
      </md>
      by the (ordinary single variable) chain rule.
      So
      <me>
      y\pdiff{z}{x}-x\pdiff{z}{y}
      =y(2x)f'(x^2+y^2)-x(2y)f'(x^2+y^2)=0
      </me>
      and the differential equation is always satisfied, assuming that
      <m>f</m> is differentiable, so that the chain rule applies.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>


    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez, si possible, une fonction <m>f(x,y)</m> pour laquelle <m>f_x(x,y)=e^y</m> et
      <m>f_y(x,y)=e^x</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      Si <m>f(x,y)</m> obéissant aux conditions spécifiées existe, alors il est nécessaire
      que <m>f_{xy}(x,y)=f_{yx}(x,y)</m>.
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      Il n'existe pas une telle fonction <m>f(x,y)</m>.
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      No such <m>f(x,y)</m> exists, because if it were to exist, then we would have
      that <m>f_{xy}(x,y)=f_{yx}(x,y)</m>. But
      <md>
      <mrow>
      f_{xy}(x,y)&amp;=\pdiff{}{y}f_x(x,y)=\pdiff{}{y}e^y=e^y
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{yx}(x,y)&amp;=\pdiff{}{x}f_y(x,y)=\pdiff{}{x}e^x=e^x
      </mrow>
      </md>
      are not equal.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>


    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez les dérivées partielles spécifiées.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y) = x^2y^3</m>;
      <m>f_{xx}(x,y)</m>, <m>f_{xyy}(x,y)</m>, <m>f_{yxy}(x,y)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y) = e^{xy^2}</m>;
      <m>f_{xx}(x,y)</m>, <m>f_{xy}(x,y)</m>, <m>f_{xxy}(x,y)</m>, <m>f_{xyy}(x,y)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>\displaystyle f(u,v,w) = \frac{1}{u+2v+3w}\ </m>,
         <m>\displaystyle \frac{\partial^3 f}{\partial u\partial v\partial w}(u,v,w)\ </m>,
         <m>\displaystyle \frac{\partial^3 f}{\partial u\partial v\partial w}(3,2,1)</m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>f_{xx}(x,y) = 2y^3</m></p><p>
          <m>f_{yxy}(x,y) = f_{xyy}(x,y) = 12xy</m>
      </p>

      <p>(b) <m>f_{xx}(x,y)= y^4e^{xy^2}</m></p><p>
          <m>f_{xy}(x,y)= \big(2y+2xy^3\big)e^{xy^2}</m></p><p>
          <m>f_{xxy}(x,y)= \big(4y^3 + 2xy^5\big)e^{xy^2}</m></p><p>
          <m>f_{xyy}(x,y) = \big(2+10xy^2+4x^2y^4\big)e^{xy^2}</m>
      </p>

      <p>(c) <m>\displaystyle\frac{\partial^3 f}{\partial u\,\partial v\,\partial w}(u,v,w)
              = -\frac{36}{(u+2v+3w)^4}</m></p><p>
          <m>\displaystyle\frac{\partial^3 f}{\partial u\,\partial v\,\partial w}(3,2,1)
               = -0.0036
               = -\frac{9}{2500}</m>
      </p>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a) We have
      <md>
      <mrow>
      f_x(x,y) &amp;= 2xy^3 &amp;
      f_{xx}(x,y) &amp;= 2y^3
      </mrow><mrow>
       &amp; &amp;
      f_{xy}(x,y) &amp;= 6xy^2 &amp;
      f_{yxy}(x,y) = f_{xyy}(x,y) &amp;= 12xy
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(b) We have
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f_x(x,y) &amp;= y^2e^{xy^2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{xx}(x,y) &amp;= y^4e^{xy^2} &amp;
      f_{xxy}(x,y) &amp;= 4y^3e^{xy^2} + 2xy^5e^{xy^2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{xy}(x,y) &amp;= 2ye^{xy^2}+2xy^3e^{xy^2}\quad &amp;
      f_{xyy}(x,y) &amp;= \big(2\!+\!4xy^2\!+\!6xy^2\!+\!4x^2y^4\big)e^{xy^2}
      </mrow><mrow>
       &amp; &amp;
       &amp;= \big(2+10xy^2+4x^2y^4\big)e^{xy^2}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>(c) We have
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \pdiff{f}{u}(u,v,w) &amp;= -\frac{1}{(u+2v+3w)^2}
      </mrow><mrow>
      \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial u\,\partial v}(u,v,w) &amp;= \frac{4}{(u+2v+3w)^3}
      </mrow><mrow>
      \frac{\partial^3 f}{\partial u\,\partial v\,\partial w}(u,v,w)
              &amp;= -\frac{36}{(u+2v+3w)^4}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      In particular
      <md>
      <mrow>
      \frac{\partial^3 f}{\partial u\,\partial v\,\partial w}(3,2,1)
              &amp;= -\frac{36}{(3+2\times 2+3\times 1)^4}
               = -\frac{36}{10^4}
               = -\frac{9}{2500}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>


    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez toutes les dérivées partielles de deuxième ordre de <m>f(x,y)=\sqrt{x^2+5y^2}</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      <m>f_{xx}=\frac{5y^2}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}</m></p><p>
      <m>f_{xy}=f_{yx}=-\frac{5xy}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}</m></p><p>
      <m>f_{yy}=\frac{5x^2}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      Let <m>f(x,y)=\sqrt{x^2+5y^2}</m>. Then
      <md>
      <mrow>
      f_x&amp;=\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+5y^2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{xx}&amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+5y^2}}-\frac{1}{2}\frac{(x)(2x)}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}} &amp;
      f_{xy}&amp;=-\frac{1}{2}\frac{(x)(10y)}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y&amp;=\frac{5y}{\sqrt{x^2+5y^2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{yy}&amp;=\frac{5}{\sqrt{x^2+5y^2}}-\frac{1}{2}\frac{(5y)(10y)}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}&amp;
      f_{yx}&amp;=-\frac{1}{2}\frac{(5y)(2x)}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      Simplifying, and in particular using that <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+5y^2}}
      =\frac{x^2+5y^2}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}</m>,
      <md>
      <mrow>
      f_{xx}&amp;=\frac{5y^2}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}\qquad
      f_{xy}=f_{yx}=-\frac{5xy}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{yy}&amp;=\frac{5x^2}{(x^2+5y^2)^{3/2}}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>


    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez toutes les dérivées partielles spécifiées.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xy}}\big)</m>; <m>f_{xyz}(x,y,z)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xy}}\big)
                  +\arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xz}}\big)
                  +\arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{yz}}\big)</m>; <m>f_{xyz}(x,y,z)</m>
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xyz}}\big)</m>; <m>f_{xx}(1,0,0)</m>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <hint><p>
      (a) Cette dérivée partielle d'ordre supérieur peut être évaluée de manière extrêmement efficace
      en choisissant soigneusement l'ordre d'évaluation des dérivées.
      </p>

      <p> Cette dérivée partielle d'ordre supérieur peut être évaluée de manière extrêmement efficace
      en choisissant soigneusement un <em>différent ordre d'évaluation</em> des dérivées
      pour chacun des trois termes.
      </p>

      <p>(c) Posez <m>g(x) = f(x,0,0)</m>. Alors, <m>f_{xx}(1,0,0)=g''(1)</m>.
      </p></hint>

      <answer><p>
      (a) <m>f_{xyz}(x,y,z)=0</m></p><p>
      (b) <m>f_{xyz}(x,y,z)=0</m></p><p>
      (c) <m>f_{xx}(1,0,0)=0</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)
      As <m>f(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xy}}\big)</m> is independent of <m>z</m>,
      we have <m>f_z(x,y,z) = 0</m> and hence
      <me>
      f_{xyz}(x,y,z)
      =f_{zxy}(x,y,z)
      =0
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>(b) Write <m>u(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xy}}\big)</m>,
                <m>v(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xz}}\big)</m> and
                <m>w(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{yz}}\big)</m>.
      Then
      <ul>
      <li>
      As <m>u(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xy}}\big)</m> is independent of <m>z</m>,
      we have <m>u_z(x,y,z) = 0</m> and hence
      <m>
      u_{xyz}(x,y,z)
      =u_{zxy}(x,y,z)
      =0
      </m>
      </li>
      <li>
      As <m>v(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xz}}\big)</m> is independent of <m>y</m>,
      we have <m>v_y(x,y,z) = 0</m> and hence
      <m>
      v_{xyz}(x,y,z)
      =v_{yxz}(x,y,z)
      =0
      </m>
      </li>
      <li>
      As <m>w(x,y,z) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{yz}}\big)</m> is independent of <m>x</m>,
      we have <m>w_x(x,y,z) = 0</m> and hence
      <m>
      w_{xyz}(x,y,z)
      =0
      </m>
      </li>
      </ul>
      As <m>f(x,y,z)=u(x,y,z)+v(x,y,z)+w(x,y,z)</m>, we have
      <me>
      f_{xyz}(x,y,z)=u_{xyz}(x,y,z)+v_{xyz}(x,y,z)+w_{xyz}(x,y,z)=0
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>(c) In the course of evaluating <m>f_{xx}(x,0,0)</m>, both <m>y</m> and <m>z</m> are held fixed at <m>0</m>. Thus, if we set <m>g(x) = f(x,0,0)</m>, then  <m>f_{xx}(x,0,0)=g''(x)</m>.
      Now
      <me>
      g(x) = f(x,0,0) = \arctan\big(e^{\sqrt{xyz}}\big)\Big|_{y=z=0}
                      =\arctan(1)
                      =\frac{\pi}{4}
      </me>
      for all <m>x</m>. So <m>g'(x)=0</m> and <m>g''(x)=0</m> for all <m>x</m>. In particular,
      <me>
      f_{xx}(1,0,0) = g''(1) = 0
      </me>
      </p>

      </solution>
    </exercise>
